{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921011501/0019.xml":{"full_text":"Hargrove's Far Quality\nWHEB\u2014\nSUCHA\nWIND!-!\nA\nGET A CAP!\nAT\nHALF PRICE\nSAVE HANGING ON\nTO YOUR HAT FOR\nDEAR LIFE WITH BOTH\nHANDS.\n$1.50* $2, $2.50\nGreat Falls' Best Cap Shop\nEXPRESS COMPANY\nPLA NS CAM PAIGN\nAim to Educate Shippers in\nShipping Methods; Dwyer\nNames Committee.\nPlans for a campaign to educate the\npublic here in tlie methods of express\nhandling to enable them to co-operate\nwith express companies were announc\ned Friday by T. J. Dwyer, genci-al\nagent for the American Railway Ex\npress company here.\nThe movement is in line with a na\ntional-wide 'ompai^ii of the express\ncompanies 'o adopt permanent pro\ngram of education in express hand\u00fcng\nmethods. Cff-nperation of express\nshippers with the companies is one of\nthe ultimate aims of the plan, accord\ning to Mr. Dwyer.\n\"Right Way\" committees, selected\nfrom employas of the American Ex\npress company, have been appointed\nby Mr. Dwyer to carry on the educa\ntional campaign in Grent Pal's. Chair\nman of the committes are: Mr. M. S.\nLeOore, office employes M. White, de\npot employ\u00bb\u00ab; It. W. Ellis vehicle men:\nA Weaver messengers' department.\nThe comniitte members will explain\nto express patrons proper ways of\npacking and ji.vking shipments ami the\ncorrect method of filing claims on ship\nments.\nOver 22,000 People\nVisit Glacier Park\nin Last Year, Report\nThe total number of people regis\ntered at National Glacier Park in HH'O\nwas according to J. F. Ilerkett. travel\ning passenger agent for the Great\nNorthern railway here, who has jnst\nreceived fia: ires on the park attend\nence for K*20 from St. Paul headquart\ners.\n<>f the number 12.1 SO entered\nthrough t>!e Glacier park gateway\nwhile 8.<\u00bb7L' entered through the Helt\non station entrance. The number cn\nIteriug through the Waterton lake en\n.Jtrane* from Canada was 1.48S. Four\nhundred and twenty-two people enter\ned the park on foot, according to the\n^report.\ni\nA\n<r\n^sr\nIs it Your Home\nThey are Plan\nning to Rob?\nBURGLABS and thieves\nare everywhere\nwatching your movements\n\u2014looking for unlocked win\ndows\u2014waiting for an op\nportunity to rob.\nEven now, while you\nfancy yourself secure, they\nmay be planning to rob\nyour home. Protect your\nself while you can.\nJET NA-IZE\n\u00a3tot Combination Residence\nProtection reimburses you for\nlosses occasioned by burglars,\nthieves or dishonest servants, be\nthe amount large or small.\nIn the same contract you are in\nsured against loss from hold-up,\nwater damage, glass breakage,\nliability for accidental Injuries and\nloss of use.\nLet us quote you rates for this\ncomptes protection.\nHUNTSBERGER-GIVENS CO.\nI Phone 4334 I Vi Third St. So.\nA\nDONE BY\nSecretary Scott Leavitt Points to Achievements\nof Organization in City, State and\nNational Undertakings.\nReview of the work done in the\npast year by the Great Falls Commer\ncial club was given by Secretary Scott\nLeavitt in his annual report. He said:\n\"No year has demonstrated more\nfully than 1020 tht\u00c9 in Great Falls\nthere dominates the spirit which builds\ncities. The conditions of agriculture,\nindustry and finance which determine\nthe general business policy of a com\nmunity reflect also in the year activ\nities of a commercial club. Therefore,\n1920 has not been a spectacular year.\nBut on the other hand, it has been\none of constructive foundations. That\nGreat Falls has met the year with a\nfine optimism is well illustrated by\nthe impression made on the- accredited\nrepresentative of the Eos Angeles\nChamber of Commerce, here this sum\nmer with the national park-to-park\ntour. His statement appears in the\nJanuary 1, 1921, issue of the Motor\nWest, a magazine of wide circulation\npublished at Los Angeles, and he\nsays:\n'Great Falls impresses you as one\nof the real live business towns of the\nwest substantially and permanently\nbuilt, and every man there means busi\nness. Our party had particular rea\nson to remember Great Falls, owing\nto the exceedingly fine treatment re\nceived at the hotels and garages. Not\nevery town on the tour has the keen\nvision thnt marks Great Falls.\"\n\"This is not a year when industries\nwere making large investments, but\nmuch work has been done which will\nbear fruit in due season. No oil re\nfinery has j\"et been built in Montana,\nbut this club has kept in touch w.th\nthe situation and conferred by corre\nspondence, and personally with those in\na position to advise the right course of\naction. There were, however, several\nthings of large importance to which\nthe attention of the club could be\nturned to advantage. I will speak of\nsome of them briefly in order.\nIrrigation Work Accomplished.\n\"Through the irrigation committee.\nL. L. Callaway, chairman, ths club\nworked with the locnl administration\nof the U. S. reclamation service; as\nsisted in showing the congress onal ap\npropriations committee over the Sun\nriver irrigation project, and consist\nently workrtl to secure the favorable\nreport to that committee for the ap\npropriation of $(>87.000 for the Sun\nr'ver project and $1.213,000 for the\nMilk river project; co-operated with\nthe reclamation service in securing\nan educational film, and. assisted\nthrough a special committee in raising\nfunds for the Montana irrigation con\ngress. By co-operation with the rec\nlamation service and the appropria\ntions committee, we thus ass sted in\nsome degree to seenre the watering of\napproximately 125.000 additional acres\nof irrigated lands contiguous to Great\nFalls in the Sun river project alone.\nThe club was also represented by a\ndirector ar.d its secretary at Seattle.\nSeptember 1C> and 17. in the forming of\nthe Northwestern States Irrigation\nDevelopment association.\nRoad Buiiding Favored.\nHaving been instrumental in pass\ning the county road bond measure in\n101K and in the making of application\nby ascade county for\n-ral road money in 1919. the club con-|\ntinned its co-operation with the county\ncommissioners and the state highway\ncommision in the partial expenditures\nof this money in 1920. The form of,\nread construction is approved by the\nU. S. bureau of public roads, and Cas\ncade county is now well on the way\nto having one of the best trunk _ high\nway systems in the state. Critics of\nconstruction must remember that we\ncan not have good roads while we are\nbuilding them and thnt the new con\nstruct'on has as yet had no moisture\nupon it.\n\"The major roiid project was the\nNational Park-to-Pork Highway, of\nwhich the Y-G Bee Line lia\u00ab become a\npart. The Commercial club under\nwrote Montana's portion of the ex\npense of the pathfinding and publicity\ntours necessary to the establishing of\nthe 5,500 mile route through Great\nFalls and connecting the National\nParks of the west in a great circle.\nIn this wc cooperated with Denver, the\nYellowstone highway towns of Wyom\ning and the other Y-G Bee Line towns\nof Montana and had the support of\nthe American Automobile Association\nand the National Park Service of the\nDepartment of the Interior. Wade II.\nGeorge, chairman of the Good Roads\ncommittee, raised a considerable por\ntion of this fund in Great Falls and\nthe club started in securing the allot\nment of other Montana towns. Thus\nthe expense did not come from the\nclub treasury, except as to the sec\nretary's salary. This was met in the\nsame way the Denver f J ourist and Pub\nlic'ty H uro nn and the Cody, \\Yyo., or\nganization provided for the time of an\nofficial each.\nMovement Is Important.\n\"The importance and official chnr\nater of this movement is emphasized in\nthe annual report of the secretary of\nthe interior, John Barton Payne, and\nwe will continue tp cash in on th.s\ninvestment as long as we are a city.\n\"The building of the Blackfeet In\ndian reservation road has long been\nan important problem, and its con\nstruction has been materially advanced\nby our connect on with this national\nmovement, and the club was also in\nstrumental in having Honorable Cato\nSells, United States commissioner of\nIndian affairs, go over the road per\nsonally, after which he promised fav\norable action.\nThe Road Through Glacier.\n\"A road through Glacier park has\nalso been a necessity to bring us our\nshare of through travel. This has bee.\nadvanced by the report of the secre\ntary of the interior, who refers to it\nas the most important construction\nproblem in any of the national parks\nfor 1921, stating that it is the one miss\ning link in the National l'ark-to-Park\nHighway. At the same tjme the state\nhighway commission, after conference\nwith this and other clubs, has made\nsurvey of the route along the Great\nNorthern railway and the forest service\nhas worked wit* Glacier county in\nbuilding a few miles west from Glacier\nstation. The Importance of our whole\nmovement in connection with the na\ntional park travel is shown by the fate\nthat the number of automobiles enter\ning the parks increased from 97,721 in\n1919 to 128,074 in 1920. Gteat Falls\nshould become the gateway Jo Glacier\npark just as Tienver is to the Rocky\nMountain National park.\n\"Locally, also, the club has contin\nually worked for truck roads leading\ninto every agricultural section about us,\nand the practical complctioin of the two\nconcrete bridges aggregating $467,000\nmarks an achievement in which the\nCommercial club has had a part from\nthe beginning.\nConventions Held Here.\n\"Thirty-five conventions of major im\nportance beides several gatherings of\nlesser import were held in Great Falls\nin 1920. The Commercial club, with\nJ. R. llobbins chairman of the enter\ntainment committee and A. P. Ileaney\nchairman of the automobile committee,\ntook a leading part in entertaining\nthe majority of them and co-operated\nwith other organizations in entertain\ning others. Statewide and even nation\nal notice was given to our entertain\nment of the Montana Association of\nCommercial Organisation Secretaries;\nmembers of the St. Paul delegation and\nother visitors at the Livestock Pavilion\ndedication; the Montana Department\nof the United Spanish War Veterans;\nthe Minneapolis Trade Tour; the Mon\ntana Retail Merchants Association, in\nwhich the local Merchant Association\ntook the lead; the regional convention\nof the League of Woman Voters; the\nMontana Municipal League, 4;he Appro\npriations Committee of the National\nCongress; the pathfinding and publicity\ntours of the National Park-to-I'ark\nHighway; the Society of Montana Pio\nneers an<] the Sons and _Daughters of\nMontana Pioaeers: the Y -G Bee Line\nannual meeting; the Montana Federa\ntion of Woman's club.?, and. the State\nDairymen's Association. These, how\never, were only part of the total, a\nmore complete list of which follows:\n\"Montana Gra n Growers' associa\ntion, January 6-7.\n\"Montana poultry show, Januarv\n19-24.\n\"Montana Association of Commer\ncial organization secretaries, February\n10-11.\n\"Montana Abstractors' association.\nFebruary 13-14.\nI./-\nCascade county farm bureau agri\ncultural counc.l. February LS.\nMontana co-operators congress,\ne aI\nMcntana federation of Labor,\n,.V,\" arv\nMontana retail implement dealers,\nMarch 2-3.\n\"Montana Millers' association,\nMarch 6.\n\"Montana automobile show, March\n^_<>n\n15-20.\n\"Montana livestock pavilion dedica\ntion, April 19.\n\"United Spanish war veterans of\nMontana, May fi-7.\n\"Montana Shorthorn Breeders' as\nsociation. May 0.\n\"Scott'sh Iiite Masons. May 4-7.\n\"County agents and home demon\nstration agents. May 7.\n\"Montana wholesale grocers, Mav\n10-11.\n\"Woodmen of the World. May 19.\n\"State hotel men, May 20.\n\"Montana Hereford Breeders' asso\nciation. May 21.\n\"Montana State Dental association,\nMay 24-30.\n\"Minneapolis trade tour, May 2<i.\n\"Regional convention league of wo\nm<J|1 votPrs j un jft-20.\n\"Retail Merchants' Association of\nj u j -j3-14-ir;.\nT{ r hekah lodire .Tulv 22\n-Congressional appropriai\nj u y of,.\nappropriations com\nmittee July 27.\n\"Spokane delegation in connection\nwith Northwestern irrigation nssoeia\n\"Y-G Bee line, August 9.\n\"Electrical dealers, August 22-23.\n\"Society of Montana pioneers, Sep- j\ntember 9-10. j\n\"Sons and daughters, September\n9-10.\n\"Montana municipal league, Septem\nber 23-24-25.\n\"Montana Federation of Women's\nclubs, October 20-27.\n\"State Dairymen's association, De\ncember 9-10.\n\"Annual meeting Cascade county\nfarm bureau. December IS.\n\"District meeting M. E. church, Jan\nuary 3-4-5.\nLuncheon Meetings and Gatherings.\n\"Important luncheon meeting in\nwhich the membership and invited or\nganizations participated included;\n\"Harry R. Cunningham of Helena\nand Chancellor E. C. Elliott of the\nState university, February 11.\n\"Guy L. Conant, boy scout executive\nof Lewistown, March 10.\n\"Gus Holm's, president of the Na\ntional park-to-park highway of <\"'ody,\nWyo., and the Mare Island marine\nband, April 20.\n\"Colvin B. Brown, organization chief\nof the U. S. \"Chamber of Commerce,\nWashington, D. C.. June 7.\n\"Colonel A. L Wertgard; field rep\nresentative of the American Automo\nA 60,0G0-lb. Car of Fresh Hand Selected\nPOTATOES\nJust In and More to Follow in Quick Order\nFrom Simms, Mont.\nThe Fountain of high quality Potatoes Snd Garden Truck.\nNetted Gem Potatoes, per cwt\nIrish Cobblers Potatoes, per cwt\nRural New Yorkers, Potatoes, per cwt.\nEarly Olflo Potatoes, per cwt.\nDanish Ball Head Cabbage. $2.50 cwt; 33 lbs.\nOnions, A3.00 cwt., 30 lbs\nRutabagas, f2.25 cwt., 35 lbs\nCarrots, 92.0 cwt., 35 lbs\nTable Beets. \u00a32.50 cwt.. 33 lbs.\nParsnips, \u00c74.00 cwt., 20 lbs\n91.75\n1.75\n1.75\nfl.75\nfl.OO\n\u00abl.OO\nii.oo\nIl.OO\nfl.OO\n411.00\nDon t worry about quality. If you are not pleased you get them free.\nWe send out notlmg but the finest. We ship out orders to any point\non days railroads furnish heated service. Free delivery to carriers and\ncity.\nSIMMS TRUCK GARDENS\nDALY BLOCK\n204 Fourth St. So.\nfe\n11\nbile association, Washington, D. C.,\nJuly 9.\n\"Harry N. Burhans, president of the\nAmerican Travel Development^ asso\nciation, Denver, Colo.; L. L Newton,\npresident of the Wyoming State Good\nRoads association; O. Van Wyck of\nthe national park service, and other\nofficials. September 10.\n\"On May 25 the International joint\nwaterways commission of Canada and\nthe United States were given a com\nmittee dinner .and on July 26 a com\nmittee breakfast was given the con\ngrcss onal appropriations committee.\nThe \u00abmoker tendered the Minneapolis\ntrade tour on May 26 was one of the\nreal events of the year, as was also\nthe picnic on King's Hill, September 9.\nTraffic Department.\n\"The traffic, manager, H. P. Schif\nfer, lias prepared a separate report of\nthe activities of his department and I\nwill only say that, under his efficient\nleadership and that of the traffic com\nmittee, headed by F. J. Gies, we\nworked successfully to relieve the car\nshortage last spring; to secure contin\nuation of low rates on hay and stock\nfeed; to adjust intrastate freight rates\nto eliminate discrimination against this\nlocality; to secure convenient and\nprofitable train service into and out\nof Great Falls for our wholesalers\nand others; to advance the movement\nfor the Great Lakes-St. Lawrence\nriver canal, and in general to make of\nGreat Falls a more satisfactory manu\nfacturing and jobbing center. The\nconvenience and advantage of the traf\nfic department in checking freight bills\nand quoting freight rates is well es\ntablishedr I desire to speak also of\nthe valuable co-operation of J. W.\nGoodman formerly our traffic man\nager, in carrying to completion some\nof the work started under his admin\n\u00abistrat on.\nCo-Operation With Farmers.\n\"Reduced rates on hay and stock\nfeed, co-operation with the farm bu\nreau in helping out the shortage of\n_\nj harvest labor, advancing the move\n\u00bb\"ont to relieve drouth sufferers, were\nj 80mo ^nannels through which\n%v c worked, \\\\ithont encroaching on\nl iii'wm, v. il I\u00bb iLiiriJi iiuiin o m j v.\nPalls and surrounding country\n)lfj a home, farming and business op\nportn nity. In addition to the film.\nwhich becomes the property of the\nclub, prints are made for the Red\nCross community service, the United\nStates r*\" lamation service, the bureau\nof visual education, and the bureau of\ncummercial economics, all national or\nganizations, insuring (he widest pos\ns |ile showing for a period of vears at\ni .1 1_ J\nthe fields of the farm bureau or other\nfarmers' organizations, we gave them\nour support.\nPublicity Work Done.\n\"Material was gathered and plates\nsecured for a 1921 booklet, the supply\nof books already on hand sufficing for\n1920. The publicity work, aside from\nthe nation-wide advertising in maga\nzines and newspapers or through maps\nof national circulation as a result of\nour participation in the park-to-park\nmovement, was largely centered in the\n2.0<>0 feet of motion picture film taken\nin co-operation with the United States\nreclamation service. The film has been\nviewed and titles are now being at\ntached- It shows livestock, farming,\nmanufacturing, irrigation, roads, scen\nerv. schools, churches, homes-\u2014in fact\nfarmers' meetings, schools and uni\nversities and before industrial groups.\nTourist Automobile Camp.\n\"In common with other Montana and\nwestern cities, we began a movement\nto build a tourist camp with a special\ncommittee headed by W. A. Bertke\nin charge. The co-operation of the\npark hoard and the city eouneil was\nsecured and Mr. Ilennihoffer. the park\nsuperintendent, gave enthusiastic and\nvaluable assistance. Permanent build\nings and conveniences are being built\nand the completion of the plan will\nSP( this one of the best camps in the\nwest- Gas for cooking and all sani\ntary conveniences are in the plan and\nsite on the Missouri river, near\nthe business and theater district and\nthe garages, insures maximum results\nto the business man. The time has\ncome when many travelers go by a city\nwithout these conveniences, and the\nSt. Paul association said, as late as\nDecember, that the convention and\ntourist business is the greatest busi\nness in the United States today.\nThe Boy Scouts.\n\"Through the Rotary club 135 sus\ntaining contributors were secured in\n1020 for the Boy Scout movement.\nThe Commercial club brought Scout\nExecutive Ponant from Lewistown\nand arranged a largely attended lunch\nat. which he put the scout program\nbefore our people. We further made\nthe success of the movement sure\nwhen we offered office room for the\nScout Executive. Mr. Graybill. and the\nheadquarters of the scouts has been\nwith the Commercial club since the\nbeginning.\nGeneral Activities.\n\"Manv more activities of the club\nfor 1920 deserve mention in detail,\nbut I shall \u00bbonly summarize some of\nthem. We\u2014\n\"Further assisted the Montana Live\nstock Pavilion company in the dedi\ncation of the pavilion, making it an\naffair of state importance.\n\"Worked through a committee on a\nmunicipal landing field and gathered\ndata for the establishing of such a\nfield.\n\"Co-operated through the services\nof the secretary and otherwise with\nthe Red Cross.\n\"Assisted morally and financially\nand by securing autos in the dandelion\ncampaign -and picnic.\n\"Co-operated w th the Theodore\nRoosevelt Internat ional Highway as\nsociation of the northern Montona tier\nof counties in securing the routing of\nthat road through northern Montana\nand Glacier park.\n\"Took part by delegate in the na\ntional educational conference at Butt\u00ab.\n\"Assisted community movements at\nCh nook, Ilarlem, Havre, Conrad und\nSimms.\n\"Sent delegates to the international\nwaterways conference nt Helene, to\nopen the Great Lakes-St. Lawrence\nway to the sen.\n\"Helped check census results.\n\"Worked to secure aeroplane pat;* )1\nof Montana forests.\n\"Put a float in the fire prevention\nparade and generally assisted that\nmovement.\n\"Worked for the enforcement of\nthe anti-dumping clause of the present\nfar iff law to protect our producers\nagainst Canadian wheat.\n\"Gave first prisse for army essay\ncontest to stimulate Americanism.\n\"Secured 190 new members by a\nquiet campaign and without a drive.\n\"Helped materially by our activi\nties in maintaining that community\nspirit and morale which have made\nGreat Falls known among the cijies.\n\"During the year there have been\nmany evidences of faith in our city\nA hotel of the first class hes been\ncompleted and opened: a large factory\nis under way; one of the finest theater\nbuildings, according to the architect, in\nthe United Stages, to cost around\n$400,000 when completed and equipped,\na new business block in course of erec\ntion; extensions projected to present\nindustries which would be immensely\ngratifying if they could be announced\nat this time; yil prospecting going for\nward in contiguous territory with\nthousands of new money coming in;\nfunds well along for a new business\nand office building to represent, an\ninvestment of $000,000; irrigation plans\nmaterially advanced; business and fi\nnancial institutions holding steady on\na conservative basis ready for the fu\nture.\n\"With regret we record the loss of\none of our 1 most valuable directors.\nSamuel S. Singer, and of the one hon\norary director of the club, Hon. Taris\nGibson. Undoubtedly one of the 1921\nactivities of the club should be con\nsideration of a suitable memorial for\nthe \"Father of Great Falls.\" To the\nvision, genius and labor of these two\nmen, Great Falls and this Commercial\nclub owe much.\n\"With pleasure I acknowledge the\nco-operation of the directors and mem\nbers of the club, of the office force\nand of Aim011 LeFebvre, who carried\non much of the work during my ab\nsence.\n\"Undoubtedly 1921 should see in\naugurated several methods of work\nwhich I have had opportunity to study\nin other cities and in the publications\nof the American City Bureau and the\nUnited States Chamber of Commerce,\nmethods which bring the work of the\nclub closer to the membership and\nmake of the membcrsh p a more ac\ntive working force in the organization.\nThese recommendations will be laid\nbefore the new board- The retiring\npresident. Mr. O. S. Warden, whose\nwork for 1920 deserves your sincere\ncommendation, has made suggestions\nas to major activities for 1921, with\nwhich I agree..\"\n(Continued from Pnire Five.)\ncity at the beginning of January with\nout coal and reasonable food. We\nare looking ont for our neighbor bet\nter than we used to and this is right.\nEvery commercial institution in the\ncity makes up the warp and woof of\noui- business fabric. We cannot afford\nto break a single thread by rivalries\nthat are inconsiderate, by tearing down\nwhat can be saved, or by evil report\nthat is almost criminal if it is care\nless. In these days, one should try\nto keep his own business safe and to\nh'dp his neighbor as much as he can.\nThe banker may encourage each hon\nest patron if he cannot loan him\nmoney. The business man can talk\nup to his customer, if he cannot ex\ntent! him credit. It makes a mighty\nbig difference because what these men\nsay is reported in the home and on the\nstreet and everywhere.\nWhen business men go through diffi\nculties shoulder to shoulder\u2014that\ncommunity is ready for the sun of\nprosperity whether it rises today or\ntomorrow.\nState is Producer of Wealth.\n\"I would not presume to pull on the\nshoes of a prophet but I do believe a\nfew things that are good if they are\nsensible.\n\"In the first year of the future, when\nthere is 2 reasonable business situation\nover the whole country and fair yield\ning conditions in this state. Montana\nwill produce more wealth per capita\nthan any other commonwealth in the\nwhole Union. This state can now make\na more diversified and wonderful agri\ncultural exhibit of its productions than\nmi\n\u00abCe\nOUR A&SOETMgNT l& A WINNe*.?\nTHE VALLEY MARKET\nWE DELIVER =PHOWE 9578\nIn the History of\nThe Butcher Business\nno finer collection of\nmeats has ever been dis\nplayed to a particular\npublic than the assort\nment of meat foods we\nare offering. You can be\nsatisfied of the undoubt\ned nutriment virtue of\nour meats by visiting our\nmarket.\nFresh Dressed Poultry, Turk\u00e9ys, Geese, Ducks and\nChickens.\nOur Line of Fresh Meats are the best that money can\nbuy. Let us serve you today.\nMARKET SPECIALS\nSugar Cured Skinned Hams 32 1-2^\nSugar Cured Rolled Shoulders (boneless) 32 l-2<?\nSugar Cured Picnics, fresh stock 25^\nSugar Cured Wide Bacon, extra fancy 35<*\nLard, 3 lb. pail, 75# o lb. pail $1.25 10 lb.\npail $2.25\n-GROCERY SPECIALS\nRoyal Club Coffee, 3 lb. cans $1.20\nPowdered Skim Milk, can will make 5 quarts 45\u00a3\nSour Kraut, No. 2 cans, 3 for 25^ No. 3 cans, 2 for 25\u00a3\nExtra Good Fresh Ranch Butter, per lb .40^\nStrictly Fresh Eggs 65^\nOur line of Fancy Fresh Fruits and Vegetables is com\nplete. A look at them will convince you.\nYour Patronage Solicited at the Sign of the Electric\nSteer.\nMAI B Y TRAFFIC DEPA RTMENT\nEvery Readjustment of Rates in Which Great\nFalls or Montana Was Interested Was\nGiven Active Consideration.\n(Continued from Page Five.)\nper cent but did not allow the carriers\nto increase any of the other charges.\nGreat Lakes-St. Lawrence Project.\n\"On May 25 and 26 the International\nJoint Commission on Waterways held\nhearings in Great Falls a4d Helena, on\nthe feasibility of bringing ocean-going\nvessels into Dulutli, Minn., and other\nGreat Lakes ports via the St. Law\nrence river and the Great Lakes. In\nputt'ng this project into effect it would\nmean the slack watering of about eighty\nmiles of the St. Lawrence river, the\ncost of the project to be taken care of\nby the two governments. The Great\nFalls Commercial club went on record\nas being in favor of giving all possible\nassistance In putting this project\nthrough.\n\"The traffic department at these\nhearings furnished testimony showing\nthe benefits this territory would re\nceive in the saving on freight rates.\nFor example, take the case of wheat\nalone. The price of this commodity is\ngoverned by the world's market, which\nis ^Liverpool, England. This price is\nthe price at that point less the freight\ncharges to an ocean port. By bringing\nocean-going vessels into Duluth, Minn.,\nand other Great Lakes ports, you are\nmoving Montana 1500 miles nearer the\nworld's market, thus making a saving\nto a very large degree of the freight\ncharges from Minneapolis or Chicago\nto the Atlantic ports, which would mean\nanywhere from seven to ten ceints per\nbushel more to the producer.\n\"Another vital matter that would be\ngreatly benefited would be the car\nshortage thet confronts this territory\nyear after year, and which reached the\npeak this year, when elevators\nthroughout the state closed down on\nwhat we were doing.\nany state from ocean tp ocean. Ibis is\na proven fact. With the return of\nprosperity, Montana will, I believe, for\ninstance produce more bushels of corn\nin a favorable year than there are now\ngrown bushels of wheat. When this\nyear comes. Great Falls can take a new\nleadership part in the direction of in\ndustry, in the distribution of merchan\ndise and in the general development of\nall resources, if we begin to get ready\nnow.\n\"The end of the panic is the young\nman's opportunity. I would say to every\nyoung man, \"Save your dollars now.\nYou can lay broad foundations with\njust a few of them in a little while.\"\nMemorial to Paris Gibson.\n\"As the years come a \u00abd go, I am of\nthe opinion that the Great Fails Com\nmercial club is well nigh an essential\ninstitution if we are to build strong\nand well. A Commercial club with a\nloyal membership like our own is al\nmost sure to make a small city bigger,\nand a big city better. Do not weaken\nin the present stress. Continue ample\nmaintenance of the organization\u2014a\nsupport that is unwavering and unbrok\nen and \u00abs strong as may be possible\nunder existing conditions. Have and\nkeep the same faith in Great Falls that\nyou had when the city was growing\nfaster.\n\"Have the same faith and unswerv\ning confidence that possessed the man\nwho founded Great Falls and who or\nganized this club. Senator Paris Gib\nson. I talked with him a little while\nbefore he came to the end of his long\nand useful life. With an interest that\nwas more eager and solicitous because\nage had taken him out of its daily ac\ntivities, he asked many questions about\nHe told ine that\nthere was nothing of a public nature\nnearer to his heart. Some day, we\nshall have a part in arranging in mar\nble and bronze a fitting memorial to\nParis Gibson. If he were here at this\nnnnual session, he would say, 'I would\nrather have a strong and vigorously\nworking Commercial club within the\ncity by the falls of the Missouri as a\nmemorial to my memory than anything\nthnt can be fashioned in metal or\nchiseled in stone.' I am almost re\npeating the language of his lips. I\ncommend to you the zeal and the en\nthusiasm and the life-long work of\nParis Gibson who was a president and\nalways a director of this Commercial\nclub, as you provide and prepare for\nits welfare in the coming year.\"\naccount of being full and no railway\nequipment to haul the grain to the\nmarkets It was shown that the\nGreat Northern Railway company has\nabout 30.000 box cars suitable for\ngrain loading and that very nearly 50\nper cent of them were 011 foreign\nlines, with most of tliem east of Chi\ncago; it was also shown that at one\ntime there were 25,000 waiting to be\nunloaded at Boston on account of con\ngestion at the Atlantic ports. It takes\na car of grain or grain products from\nfour to six weeks to go from Great\nFalls to New York via the all rail\nroute through Chicago, while the av\nerage run from Great Falls to Duluth,\nMinn., is from seven to nine days.\nFigure this down to a working basis,\nit would mean that if the grain and\ngrain products could be loaded on\nboats at Duluth, it would enable the\nwestern carriers to hold their equip\nment on their own rails, and through\nthe quick turn around, would elimin\nate the car shortage in this northwest\nterritory.\n\nUn July 28, when the interstate\ndefeision on the increase in freight\nand passenger^ rates, the Montana rail\nway commission allowed the mouh\ntain intrastate freight rates to be ad\nvanced 2;> per cent as outlined by the\ncommission, but did not allow the pas\nsenger or pullman rates to be in\ncreased. November 10. the interstate\ncommerce commission held a hearing\nMontana Interstate Rates.\nat Helena, Montana, with the carriers,\nthe Montana railway commission and\nthe public, to show why the Montana\nintrastate passenger and pullman\ncharges should not be increased to\nthe same basis as the interstate rates.\nIhe Montana railway commission\nbased its case on the theory that the\ninterstate commerce commission did\nnot have any jurisdiction over the\nintrastate rates and that carriers had\nnot shown the three-cent fare in Mon\ntana to be unreasonable. The Great\nFalls Commercial club, with the Mon\ntana Lumber Manufacturing associa\ntion of Kalispell, submitted evidence to\nshow that the cost of operating a pas\nsenger train per mile in Montana was\napproximately 20 per cent less than\nin the east and that the three-cent\nfare as charged at the present time,\nwould net the carriers the same reve\nnue as the three and six-tenths fare\nin the east.\nMinimum Weights on Grain.\n\"During government operation of\nthe railroads the minimum weights on\ngrain products were increased from\n40.000 pounds to 00,000 pounds. The\ntraffic department of the Great Falls\nj\nIMPERIAL GROCERY\nTHE STORE OF QUALITY\n901 Third Avenue North\nPhone 5958\nPRE-WAR PRICES\nSu