 be unable to take care of 60,\n000 pounds, would be placed at\ngreat disadvantage over the larger\ndealers. Early in 1920, the commis\nsion ordered this minimum reduced to\n48,000 pounds and again on November\n10, a hearing was held in St. Louis be\nfore the interstate commerce commis\nj sion regarding the above minimum,\nThe Montana railway commission ad\nvised that they would be represented\nat this hearing and to take up with\nparties interested and ascertain what\nj minimum weights should be asked for.\nAfter taking this matter up with the\ni millers of the city, the Great Falls\nS Commercial club wrote the Montana\nrailway commission ask for the old\npre-war minimum oT 40,000, and on\nDecember 2, we were advised by the\ninterstate commerce commission that\nspecial permission to reduce the mini\nmum on grain products from 48.000\npounds to 40,000 had been granted\ncarriers.\n\"Due to the fact that the past year\nhas been one of readjustment in con\nnection with the passing of the rail\nroads froip government control to\nprivate ownership, it has not been\npossible to accomplish as much along\nconstructive lines as might have been\ndone otherwise; however, tentative\nplans are being made to enter into\na program of co-operative _ work with\nother commercial organizations of the\nstate in an effort to secure desirable\nlegislation concerning rates as affect\nthe state of Montana. Chief among\nthese at the present time is the ques\ntion of interline in state rate. _ This\nmatter is now pending a decision of\nthe supreme court as to the interpre\ntation of the transportation act of\n1920, as to whether the interstate\ncommerce commission or _ the Montana\nstate commission has jurisdiction over\nintrastate rates.\"","height":"22944","width":"19512"}}
